(43, 9, 7, 23, 35, 5, 5, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'Both passages emphasize the opening of the eyes of the blind, highlighting a theme of miraculous healing. John 9:7 describes a specific instance of this healing, while Isaiah 35:5 prophesies the future restoration of sight.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 43, 9, 11, 11, 'Go, wash in the pool of Siloam', 'Connection of Healing and Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing in the pool of Siloam as a crucial step in the healing process. The SOURCE verse describes the instruction to wash, while the TARGET passage recounts the man''s obedience to that instruction, leading to his sight being restored.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 43, 11, 37, 37, NULL, 'Healing and Sight', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and restoration. Both passages emphasize the miraculous ability of Jesus to bring sight and life, linking the healing of the blind man to the raising of Lazarus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 19, 146, 8, 8, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine healing, as both passages address the opening of the eyes of the blind. John 9:7 describes a specific act of healing, while Psalms 146:8 speaks generally of the Lord''s power to open the eyes of the blind.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 23, 8, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Shiloah and Siloam', 'This connection highlights the significance of the waters of Shiloah in Isaiah, which symbolizes spiritual nourishment, paralleling the healing act at the pool of Siloam in John. Both passages emphasize the importance of water as a means of restoration and insight.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 44, 26, 18, 18, 'came seeing', 'Healing and Spiritual Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of opening eyes, both physically in John 9:7 and spiritually in Acts 26:18. Both passages emphasize a transformation from darkness to light, illustrating the broader concept of enlightenment and healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 2, 4, 11, 11, NULL, 'Healing and Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize God''s power over physical conditions, such as sight and speech. John 9:7 illustrates a specific healing act, while Exodus 4:11 underscores God''s sovereignty in creating and controlling these abilities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 9, 2, 8, 8, 'he that sat and begged', 'Connection of Poverty and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the elevation of the poor and the blind. John 9:8 refers to a man who was blind and now seen, while 1 Samuel 2:8 speaks of lifting the beggar from the dunghill. This connection highlights God''s transformative power in restoring dignity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 9, 21, 11, 11, 'Is not this he', 'Recognition of Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition in both passages, where individuals question the identity of someone they have seen before. In John 9:8, the neighbors recognize the formerly blind man, while in 1 Samuel 21:11, Achish''s servants recognize David as a well-known figure. Both instances emphasize how public perception shapes identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 41, 10, 46, 46, 'that sat and begged', 'Blindness and Begging Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blindness and begging. In John 9:8, the man who was blind is recognized by his neighbors, while in Mark 10:46, blind Bartimeus is described as sitting by the highway side begging.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 42, 16, 20, 22, 'that sat and begged', 'Connection of Begging and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of begging and the recognition of individuals in need. Both passages feature a beggar, with the neighbors in John questioning the identity of the formerly blind man, paralleling the recognition of Lazarus at the rich man''s gate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 42, 18, 35, 35, 'that sat and begged', 'Blindness and Begging Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a blind man who is begging. This connection highlights the social condition of blindness and the act of begging in the context of healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 44, 3, 2, 11, 'Is not this he that sat and begged?', 'Healing and Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation of individuals who were previously known for their disabilities. In each case, the community recognizes them after their miraculous healings, leading to wonder and amazement.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 8, 1, 19, 19, 'Is not this he', 'Recognition of Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the community''s reaction to an individual''s changed status. In John 9:8, the neighbors question the identity of the formerly blind man, while in Ruth 1:19, the townspeople inquire about Naomi''s identity upon her return.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 21, 11, 5, 5, NULL, 'Understanding God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the mystery of divine actions. Both passages emphasize the inability of humans to fully comprehend the workings of God, whether in miraculous events or natural processes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 41, 4, 27, 27, NULL, 'Growth and Understanding of Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding miraculous events. In John 9:10, the question of how the man''s eyes were opened reflects a curiosity about the process of miracles, similar to Mark 4:27, which discusses the mysterious growth of seeds, emphasizing the unknown aspects of divine workings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 43, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Questions of Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize a question posed to Jesus regarding understanding miraculous events. The inquiries reflect a theme of seeking clarity about divine actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 43, 9, 15, 15, 'How were thine eyes opened?', 'Inquiry about Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the inquiry of the Pharisees regarding the healing of the blind man. The repeated question, ''How were thine eyes opened?'' in the first passage connects directly to their subsequent inquiry in the second passage about how he received his sight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 46, 15, 35, 35, 'How were thine eyes opened?', 'Questions of Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation through questioning. Both passages emphasize inquiries about significant changes: the opening of eyes in John and the resurrection of the dead in Corinthians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 43, 9, 6, 7, 'made clay, and anointed mine eyes', 'Healing of the Blind Man', 'Both passages emphasize the act of Jesus making clay and anointing the blind man''s eyes. They describe the same miracle, highlighting the process of healing through washing in the pool of Siloam.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 43, 9, 27, 27, 'A man that is called Jesus', 'Discipleship and Witness', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing Jesus'' actions. In both passages, the man emphasizes his experience with Jesus, suggesting a growing recognition of his role as a disciple.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 24, 36, 17, 17, 'said unto me, Go to the pool of Siloam, and wash', 'Connection of Divine Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving guidance from God. In both passages, individuals are instructed to act based on divine words, leading to significant outcomes: sight in John and the writing of God''s message in Jeremiah.', 'theme', 0.258, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 2, 2, 18, 20, 'Where is he?', 'Inquiry About a Missing Man', 'Both passages emphasize a question about the whereabouts of a man. In John 9:12, the inquiry is directed towards the healed blind man, while in Exodus 2:20, Reuel asks about the Egyptian who helped his daughters.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 43, 5, 11, 13, 'I know not', 'Connection of Healing and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing and the uncertainty of the healed individuals regarding the identity of Jesus. In each case, the healed person does not know who healed them, highlighting a common experience of miraculous intervention without recognition of the healer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 43, 7, 11, 11, 'Where is he?', 'Inquiry About Jesus'' Location', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''Where is he?'' which reflects the ongoing search for Jesus during significant events. This connection highlights the curiosity and confusion surrounding his whereabouts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 8, 3, 8, 'brought to the Pharisees', 'Connection of Judgment and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bringing individuals before authority figures, highlighting themes of judgment and mercy. In John 9:13, the blind man is brought to the Pharisees, while in John 8:3-8, the woman caught in adultery is presented to Jesus for judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 11, 46, 47, 'the Pharisees', 'Miracles and Pharisaic Response', 'Both passages emphasize the involvement of the Pharisees in response to Jesus'' miracles. In John 9:13, the healed man is brought to the Pharisees, while in John 11:46-47, they gather to discuss Jesus'' miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 11, 57, 57, 'him that aforetime was blind', 'Connection of Blindness and Authority', 'This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between Jesus and the religious authorities. In both passages, the actions of the Pharisees reflect their desire to control and investigate those who have experienced miraculous events, such as the healing of the blind man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 12, 42, 42, NULL, 'Fear of Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the influence of the Pharisees on belief and confession. In both passages, the actions of the Pharisees create a barrier for individuals, whether it is bringing the blind man to them or causing rulers to hide their belief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
